Fragment of marble stele (grave marker) of a young woman with her head bowed in sorrow ca. 350 BC found at Acharnae, Menidi, in Attica displayed at the Met Museum. It is important to note that these stelai/grave markers were made to commemorate the dead, a common human sentiment about loss & life impermanence. This stele seems to evoke a 4th c. BC epitaph found in Piraeus: "I lie here, but I do not lose your love." Greeks buried their dead outside the city walls along roads to the city gates like Kerameikos cemetery in Athens. This meant grave stelai were visible to all who entered & left the city with each passerby reading their epitaphs, thus keeping the memory of the dead alive.

The once lost, yet now found ancient Orcadian city of Skara Brae. In 1850 in the aftermath of a severe storm the settlement was rediscovered by villagers who found a robust stone that seemed out of place in its environment. Upon further inquiry they discovered what they initially thought was a house, but eventually realized it was much more than a house they were reckoning with. Skara Brae was a Neolithic village which was inhabited around 5,000 years ago by no more than 50-100 people, which although today is nothing, would have been substantial at the time. The village inhabitants were makers and users of grooved ware, a distinctive style of pottery that had recently appeared in northern Scotland. The houses used earth sheltering, being sunk into mounds of pre-existing prehistoric domestic waste known as middens. This provided the houses with stability and also acted as insulation against Orkney‚Äôs harsh winter climate.

During his lifetime, Robert the Bruce had made a vow to go on a crusade, however by the time of his death in 1329, he had left this vow unfulfilled. To uphold their fallen King's promise, a group of Scottish Knights, led by Sir James "The Black" Douglas, ventured to Spain carrying a casket containing Bruce's heart, and met up with King Alfonso XI of Castile who was leading a campaign against the Moorish Kingdom of Granada at the time. The Scottish Knights were welcomed by Alfonso XI, and made up part of the Castilian army during the besieging of castle Teba in 1330. During the fighting, the Scots found themselves cut-off from the main Castilian army, were overwhelmed and eventually defeated by the Moors. Out of all of Sir Douglas' company, only Sir Simon Locard escaped with his life intact. Sir Locard would return to the site of the battle later to retrieve the bodies of his fallen comrades and, of course, the casket containing Robert the Bruce's heart and returned them to Scotland

The blue men of the Minch, also known as storm kelpies are mythological creatures inhabiting the stretch of water between the northern Outer Hebrides and mainland Scotland, looking for sailors to drown and stricken boats to sink. They appear to be localised and unique to the Minch. They have the power to create storms, but when the weather is fine they float sleeping on or just below the surface of the water. The blue men swim with their torsos raised out of the sea, twisting and diving as porpoises do. They are able to speak, and when a group approaches a ship its chief may shout two lines of poetry to the master of the vessel and challenge him to complete the verse. If the skipper fails in that task then the blue men will attempt to capsize his ship. To amuse themselves the creatures play shinty when the skies are clear and bright at night. They are able to speak and converse with mariners and are especially vocal when soaking vessels with water spray, roaring with laughter as vessels capsize.

Shire to Shire Series: Clackmannanshire and "King's Seat" Centuries ago, the now barren hills of Clackmannanshire were convered in a thick forest which was home to one particularly enormous boar which would go into nearby towns and wreak havoc amongst the locals. The boar grew so troublesome King Malcom III sought to eradicate it by calling a grand hunt to take place. King Malcom took position atop a hill now named "King's Seat" and watched as various hunting parties set out until the boar was eventually spotted. All gave chase but one particular young man was the quickest in pursuit. He fired 3 arrows into the pig's side but, before he could deliver the final blow, the boar turned and charged his assailant, wounding him in the chest. As the boar went to strike again, the young man hastily produced his sword and thrust it into the boars neck, killing it. He then cut its head off and took it to the King. Drenched in blood, he threw the boar's head down at the King's feet, fell to his knees and died.

‚ÄòThe Seal Woman‚Äô, a 2.6 meter high statue in Mikladular Harbour up at the Faroe Islands. It depicts a Selkie, a creature that lives in the sea as a seal but can shed their seal hide to become a human on land. Lonely Scottish fishermen on the Western and Northern Isles were known to steal the seal hides from unsuspecting Selkies and marry them, sometimes having children with them. On this day 1395 John Barbour, the now cherished Scots literary figure and father of Scots poetry, died. First noted as a prominent churchman and diplomat, Barbour served as courtier to Robert II, aiding the king in several roles including as an auditor of exchequer and clerk of audit. Meanwhile, Barbour was also writing poetry. His most revered piece, a long narrative piece called The Brus, or Bruce, is to this day celebrated as an epoch of the Scots language, which he was the first pioneer of. Barbour's purpose in the poem was partly historical and partly patriotic. The poem tells tales of and around the first War of Scottish Independence between 1286 and 1332, including the legendary Battle of Bannockburn. He celebrates The Bruce (Robert I) and Douglas throughout as the flowers of Scottish chivalry, seeking freedom at all costs. A! fredome is a noble thing! Fredome mayss man to haiff liking; Fredome all solace to man giffis: He levys at ess that frely levys!

Most are endless knots, and many are varieties of basket weave knots.

url_title: Life in a small town in the far east of Russia / Spassk-Dalny VLOG
url_description: In this video I‚Äôll show you my hometown Spassk-Dalny. I‚Äôll tell you about the city‚Äôs geography, about its past and its present, and maybe about its future. Spassk is situated in the region called Primorsky Krai, 222 kilometres to the North from Vladivostok. The city‚Äôs populatin is 39,000 of people. Spassk is a monotown, which means that the city‚Äôs economy is dominated by a single industry. Our city forming enterprise is this Spassk Cement Factory that you can see in this video. In the end of the 19th century, the Russian government needed to populate these new far eastern territories and that‚Äôs why they gave free land to peasants from western parts of the Russian Empire. So, Spassk was founded by settlers from Ukraine in the 1886, it‚Äôs the year of Coca Cola foundation, by the way! I left Spassk 3 years ago when I moved to Khabarovsk to study in a university. There‚Äôs no way I want to return to Spassk and live there. Because there's no job, no cultural life and the level of life is really low. Anyway, It‚Äôs a nice town with rich history and great potential for development, but it seems that it is not going to revive in the next several decades. #Russia #PrimorskyKrai #SpasskDalny *About myself* My name is Natasha, I live in the Far East of Russia in the city of Khabarovsk, but originally I'm from a small town Spassk-Dalny. Currently I'm studying Linguistics in a university in Khabarovsk. I like languages and learning about different cultures. On this channel I'm making videos about life in Russia, our traditions and my traveling in Russian cities. Subscribe to my channel, and let's explore Russia together! Yeah Russia on Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/natsadv Support me on Patreon: https://www.patreon.com/NatashasAdventures If you liked this video about Spassk, there are other ones that might be interesting for you: Spassk in winter https://youtu.be/oVyw_08cRX4 Learn Russian letters on the streets https://youtu.be/2gFNtRkLNzk Hiking to the hill in Spasskoye village https://youtu.be/uyT7gPGczXw Music used in the video: Soul Searching - Causmic

A veiled Vestal Virgin Raffaelle Monti (1818‚Äì1881), marble, 1846‚Äì1847 "The 6th Duke of Devonshire visited the sculptor's studio in Milan, Italy, on 12 October 1846 on his way to Naples. He ordered the marble sculpture on 18 October, placing a ¬£60 deposit on the following day. The sculpture was ready to be dispatched to England in April 1847, and the Duke appears to have displayed it in Chiswick House, west of London. It first came to Chatsworth in 1999 and was shown in the Sculpture Gallery where it appeared in the 2005 film 'Pride and Prejudice', starring Keira Knightley and Matthew Macfadyen. In Ancient Rome, the Vestals were virgin priestesses whose lives were dedicated to the goddess Vesta. They were tasked to look after the sacred fire burning on her altar in the temple of Vesta, and were regarded as fundamental to the safety of Rome. The discovery of a "House of the Vestals" in Pompeii in the 18th century made Vestals a popular subject matter in art over the following 50 years."
